(42, 8, 23, 23, 54, 11, 11, NULL, 'Affliction and Tempest Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''tossed with tempest'' in both passages. In Luke, the disciples face a literal storm, while Isaiah speaks to the afflicted who are metaphorically tossed by life''s storms.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 23, 42, 8, 22, 22, NULL, 'Journey Across the Lake', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of Jesus and his disciples across the lake. The first passage describes their departure, while the second illustrates the peril they faced during the voyage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 23, 44, 27, 14, 20, 'were in jeopardy', 'Connection of Storms and Peril', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of being in jeopardy during a storm at sea. In Luke, the disciples face danger as the ship fills with water, while in Acts, the sailors encounter a tempest that leads them to despair of survival.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 23, 58, 4, 15, 15, 'in jeopardy', 'Connection of Human Experience', 'This connection highlights the shared experience of vulnerability in both passages. In Luke, the disciples face peril during a storm, while Hebrews emphasizes that Jesus understands human weaknesses and temptations.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 19, 107, 25, 29, NULL, 'Calming the Storm Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the calming of storms and the distress of those caught in them. In Luke, Jesus rebukes the wind and water, while Psalms describes the Lord commanding the stormy wind and making it calm. This connection highlights the divine authority over nature in both texts.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 42, 4, 39, 39, 'rebuked', 'Authority Over Illness and Nature', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority to rebuke and calm. In Luke 8:24, he rebukes the wind and water, while in Luke 4:39, he rebukes the fever, demonstrating his power over both natural and physical ailments.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 19, 104, 6, 9, 'rebuked the wind', 'Calming of Waters Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over chaotic waters. Both passages emphasize the power of rebuke, as seen in ''at thy rebuke they fled'' and ''he arose, and rebuked the wind.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 42, 5, 5, 5, 'Master, master', 'Authority Over Nature', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus in both passages. In Luke 8:24, He calms the storm, demonstrating His power over nature, while in Luke 5:5, Simon acknowledges Jesus as ''Master'' and obeys His command despite previous failure, showcasing trust in His authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 47, 1, 9, 10, 'we perish', 'Deliverance from Peril', 'Both passages emphasize reliance on God during dire situations. In Luke, the disciples call for help in a life-threatening storm, while in 2 Corinthians, Paul speaks of trusting God for deliverance from death. This connection highlights the theme of divine rescue in moments of crisis.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 24, 5, 22, 22, NULL, 'Calm Amidst Chaos', 'Both passages emphasize the authority over chaotic waters. In Luke, Jesus calms the storm, while Jeremiah speaks of God''s decree over the sea''s boundaries.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 24, 34, 1, 4, 4, 'rebuked the wind and the raging of the water', 'Rebuking the Sea', 'This connection highlights the authority of God over the sea in both passages. In Luke, Jesus rebukes the wind and water, while Nahum describes God rebuking the sea and drying up rivers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 40, 8, 26, 26, 'Where is your faith?', 'Connection of Faith and Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' fear and lack of faith during a storm. They highlight Jesus'' authority over nature, as he commands the winds and sea, leading to calmness.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 20, 30, 4, 4, 'commandeth even the winds and water', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority over nature, with Luke highlighting Jesus commanding the winds and waters, while Proverbs speaks of one who has ''gathered the wind in his fists'' and ''bound the waters.'' This connection highlights the divine power attributed to God and, by extension, to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 41, 4, 40, 41, 'What manner of man is this!', 'Connection of Fear and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' fear and their questioning of Jesus'' identity. They highlight the theme of faith in the face of fear, as Jesus challenges them about their lack of faith.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 40, 14, 31, 31, 'Where is your faith?', 'Connection of Faith and Doubt', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of faith in the context of fear and doubt. In Luke, Jesus questions the disciples'' faith amidst a storm, while in Matthew, he addresses Peter''s doubt as he walks on water.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 43, 11, 40, 40, 'Where is your faith?', 'Faith and Belief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith and belief in Jesus'' power. Both passages emphasize the necessity of faith to witness God''s glory and the authority of Jesus over nature and death.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 1, 1, 9, 10, 'commandeth even the winds and water', 'Authority Over Waters', 'This connection highlights the authority of God over the waters in both passages. In Genesis, God commands the waters to gather, while in Luke, Jesus commands the winds and waters, demonstrating divine power.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 25, 20, 8, 29, 29, 'commandeth even the winds and water', 'Authority Over Nature', 'Both passages emphasize divine authority over the sea and waters. Luke highlights Jesus commanding the winds and water, while Proverbs speaks of God''s decree to the sea, illustrating a shared theme of control over nature.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 26, 41, 5, 1, 20, 'country of the Gadarenes', 'Journey to the Gadarenes', 'Both passages describe Jesus arriving in the country of the Gadarenes, emphasizing the geographical setting of the miracle. This connection highlights the significance of the location where the healing of the possessed man occurs.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 26, 40, 8, 28, 34, 'country of the Gadarenes', 'Location of Jesus'' Encounter', 'Both passages describe Jesus arriving at a specific location where he encounters demoniacs. Luke refers to the ''country of the Gadarenes,'' while Matthew mentions the ''country of the Gergesenes,'' indicating a shared event in a similar geographical context.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 27, 41, 5, 2, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Demoniac Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize a man with unclean spirits who dwells among the tombs. They describe his torment and inability to be restrained, highlighting his desperate condition.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 27, 9, 19, 24, 24, 'ware no clothes', 'Nakedness and Prophetic Behavior', 'This connection highlights the theme of nakedness in both passages. The man in Luke is described as wearing no clothes, while Saul in 1 Samuel also strips off his clothes, linking their states of undress to their respective encounters with the divine.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 27, 4, 19, 16, 16, 'in the tombs', 'Connection of Uncleanliness and Tombs', 'This connection highlights the theme of uncleanliness associated with death and tombs. Both passages emphasize the presence of a man in tombs, linking spiritual and ritual impurity.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 27, 23, 65, 4, 4, 'abode in any house, but in the tombs', 'Connection of Graves and Demons', 'Both passages emphasize the association with graves and tombs, highlighting a theme of spiritual and physical desolation. The man in Luke is described as dwelling among tombs, paralleling the individuals in Isaiah who remain among the graves.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 28, 40, 8, 29, 29, 'thou Son of God', 'Demons'' Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the demons'' recognition of Jesus as the ''Son of God.'' They express fear of being tormented, highlighting a common theme of spiritual authority and confrontation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 28, 61, 2, 4, 4, 'torment me not', 'Connection Between Demons and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against evil entities. In Luke, the demons recognize Jesus'' authority and fear torment, while 2 Peter discusses the punishment of angels who sinned, indicating a parallel in the fate of rebellious beings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
